STATISTICAL METHODS. The HRV measures were natural log transformed to normalize the distribution (20). Descriptive statistics of baseline characteristics were stratiﬁed by incident AF status. We used restricted cubic splines to examine the possibility that the association between HRV and incident AF was nonlinear. A partial likelihood ratio test compared models using only a linear term with models containing both the linear and cubic spline term. We found nonlinearity with threshold effects; thus, study exposures were included in models described later as both a continuous term to compare with published studies and by creating custom categories such as RR interval between 600 and 1,000 ms as reference.

