The multivariable-adjusted dose–response relationship of inverse of heart rate (mean RR) with incident AF (Figure 1) showed a threshold effect around 1,200 ms; above this threshold (heart rate of around #50 beats/min) there was a linear relationship between mean RR interval and AF. A higher mean RR interval was associated with a higher incidence of AF that was nonsigniﬁcant after adjusting for confounders (Table 2). Further, a mean RR interval of >1,000 ms (heart rate <60 beats/min) was associated with higher incidence of AF (hazard ratio [HR]: 1.15; 95% CI: 0.99 to 1.32) compared with a mean RR interval between 600 and 1,000 ms); for a mean RR of >1,100 ms (heart rate <55 beats/min), the incidence of AF was 22% higher (HR: 1.22; 95% CI: 1.01 to 1.46) compared with those with a mean RR interval between 600 and 1,100 ms.
HRV, AF INCIDENCE, AND RELATED VARIABLES. The multivariable-adjusted dose–response relationship between HRV measures (SDNN and HF) with incident AF suggested an almost log linear relationship with threshold effect (Figure 2). A lower HRV was associated with a signiﬁcantly higher risk of incident AF for all measures of HRV (Table 2). In fully adjusted Cox proportional hazard models (model 3 of Table 2), for every 1 SD lower measure, the HR of incident AF was 1.14 for log(SDNN), 1.07 for log(root mean square of successive differences in normal-to-normal RR intervals), 1.12 for log(HF), and 1.17 for log(LF). Also, a higher sympathetic tone compared with parasympathetic tone as suggested by lower log(LF/HF) was associated with higher risk of AF (HR: 1.08; 95% CI: 1.03 to 1.14 per SD). Additional adjustment for incident CHD and incident heart failure did not inﬂuence the estimates much (Table 2).
On examining differences in the HRV–AF relationship by several characteristics (Table 3), there was no difference in the relationship by race, sex, CHD, heart failure, or beta-blocker therapy. There was a difference in association by diabetes status and age group; speciﬁcally, a much stronger association was seen among those with diabetes than those without (interaction p < 0.01), and no association was found among younger cohort participants.
The estimates did not differ appreciably after excluding AF events that occurred within 2 years of follow-up. Also, additional adjustment for betablockers did not change the estimates. Further, there was an association of smaller magnitude seen when using 10-second ECG recordings (Online Table 1).
